MAPS

Map Projections

From sphere to plane

Photo by Valentin Lacoste on Unsplash

Hole, Yunnan, China

You mean to tell me that China is under us? China is under us?
It’s not. The world is flat.
— Shaquille O’Neal

In cartography, a map projection is a way to flatten a globe’s surface into a plane in order to make a map. This requires a systematic transformation of the latitudes and longitudes of locations from the surface of the globe into locations on a plane. All projections of a sphere on a plane necessarily distort the surface in some way and to some extent. Depending on the purpose of the map, some distortions are acceptable and others are not; therefore, different map projections exist in order to preserve some properties of the sphere-like body at the expense of other properties such as angle or size.

Load Map

Natural Earth

ne_world <- ne_countries(scale = "small", returnclass = "sf")

Coordinate Reference System

Set crs

A coordinate reference system (CRS) refers to the way in which spatial data that represent the earth’s surface are flattened so that you can represent them on a 2-dimensional surface.

ne_world <- ne_world %>% st_as_sf() %>% st_set_crs(4326)

Reprojected

Orthographic

theme_opts <- theme(
  legend.position = "none",
  legend.title = element_blank(),
  axis.text = element_blank(),
  #axis.line = element_blank(),
  axis.ticks = element_blank(),
  axis.title = element_blank(),
  #panel.grid = element_blank(),
  #panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
  #panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
  panel.background = element_blank(),
  panel.border = element_blank(),
  plot.background = element_blank(),
)

v1 = ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = ne_world, color="#AAAAAA", fill="#FFFFFF", size=0.5) +
  scale_x_continuous() +
  scale_y_continuous() +
  coord_sf(crs = "+proj=ortho") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x="", # Longitude
       y="", # Latitude
       title = "Natural Earth", 
       subtitle="Orthographic") +
  theme_opts

girafe(ggobj = v1, width_svg = 16, height_svg = 9,
       options = list(opts_sizing(rescale = TRUE, width = 1.0))
)
